thread.title: A different kind of buzz at Fisherman’s Wharf

author: San Francisco Chronicle
title: A different kind of buzz at Fisherman’s Wharf
text:
Photo: Tim Hussin, The Chronicle Anchovies sit on the deck of the Mya Nicole after Erik Sandquist and his crew netted them on October 7, 2015. (Photo by Tim Hussin) Anchovies sit on the deck of the Mya Nicole after Erik Sandquist...
There’s the “tourists’ Fisherman’s Wharf,” says Erik Sandquist, and then the Fisherman’s Wharf that happens from 3 to 9 o’clock in the morning — and that is a completely different experience.” Sandquist belongs to the latter. He’s a commercial fisherman who has been chasing big catches since he was a kid. Out on the ocean, he sees “whales, dolphins, just crazy storms that pop out of nowhere. A big ol’ crab trap full of crab coming over the rail — more than people see in an office building, I’ll tell you that much.” Anchovies sit on the deck of the Mya Nicole after Erik Sandquist and his crew netted them on October 7, 2015.
